# /discover-personas: Bootstrap the Shared Persona Registry

You are a UX researcher doing just the first step of a UX audit: figuring out
who uses the application. No workflow scripting, no friction scoring, no
fixes. Just personas.

The output is a single file at `.gstack/ux-audit/personas.md` that every
persona-aware hstack skill reads. Once this file exists, /ux-audit,
/auto-ux-audit, /auto-ux-audit-full, /feature-build, /auto-feature-build, and
/auto-feature-build-full all reuse it.

## Setup

{{BROWSE_SETUP}}

```bash
export BROWSE_CMD_TIMEOUT=1000
mkdir -p .gstack/ux-audit
```

## Phase 1: Check for existing registry

```bash
cat .gstack/ux-audit/personas.md 2>/dev/null
```

If a registry already exists, present it and AskUserQuestion:
- A) Keep as-is (nothing to do)
- B) Add personas
- C) Remove personas
- D) Start fresh (archives the old file)

## Phase 2: Discovery

### 2A. Ask the user

AskUserQuestion:

"Who uses this application? For each persona, tell me:
- Role name
- What they're trying to accomplish (their goal)
- How they authenticate (credentials or 'none')
- How often they use it (daily / weekly / occasional / first-time)

Or choose:
A) I'll describe them
B) You auto-discover from the app
C) Both — I'll describe mine and you discover more"

RECOMMENDATION: Choose C — combining user knowledge with app signals gives
the best coverage.

### 2B. Auto-discover from the app (if chosen)

```bash
$B goto <target-url>
$B snapshot -i
$B links
```

Check for:
- Login / signup pages → authenticated users
- `/admin` / `/dashboard` routes → admin/manager roles
- Public content without auth → visitor persona
- Role selectors, account type choosers → distinct user types
- Different navigation items when logged in vs logged out

```bash
$B goto <target-url>/admin
$B snapshot -i
$B goto <target-url>/login
$B snapshot -i
$B goto <target-url>/signup
$B snapshot -i
```

Also grep the codebase for role definitions:

```bash
setopt +o nomatch 2>/dev/null || true
grep -rn "role\|permission\|isAdmin\|userType\|user_type" --include="*.ts" --include="*.tsx" --include="*.js" --include="*.jsx" --include="*.rb" --include="*.py" -l | head -10
```

### 2C. Merge + deduplicate

Merge user-provided and discovered personas. Deduplicate on role name +
goal. Present the final list for confirmation before writing.

## Phase 3: Build + Write the Registry

For each confirmed persona, build this structured entry:

```
ID: P{n}
Role: {name}
Goal: {one-sentence goal}
Auth: {credentials or 'none'}
Entry point: {URL}
Frequency: {daily | weekly | occasional | first-time}
Permissions: {capabilities}
```

Write the full list to `.gstack/ux-audit/personas.md` with a header:

```
# Persona Registry

Generated: {YYYY-MM-DD}
Updated by: /discover-personas

## PERSONA REGISTRY

ID: P1
...
```

## Phase 4: Next-step suggestions

Announce:

> Persona registry saved to `.gstack/ux-audit/personas.md`.
> Next step — pick one:
> - `/ux-audit` — report friction across all personas
> - `/auto-ux-audit` — fix friction for one persona
> - `/auto-ux-audit-full` — fix friction for all personas
> - `/define-workflows` — derive expected workflows per persona (feeds /feature-build)
> - `/auto-feature-build` — build missing workflows for one persona

## Rules

1. **Read-first.** If a registry exists, offer to reuse before overwriting.
2. **Never fabricate personas.** Only create entries the user confirmed or
   that are observable in the app.
3. **Single source of truth.** The registry lives at
   `.gstack/ux-audit/personas.md`. Do not duplicate it elsewhere.
4. **Confirmation before write.** Always present the final list before
   writing the file.
